<TITLE> London Scottish Bank says to reduce lending </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Jan 22 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British consumer lender London Scottish Bank said on Tuesday it would cut lending until it had reduced a shortfall in capital required by regulators. London Scottish Bank (LSB) said last month it would take a charge of up to 22 million pounds ($43 million) to cover losses at its unsecured consumer credit business and that as a result its regulatory capital would be 13 million pounds short of the amount required by new banking rules. It has since been in talks with Britain's financial watchdog. "The company has prepared and submitted to the FSA (Financial Services Authority) a plan to remedy the shortfall in its regulatory capital," LSB said in a statement. "One element of this plan involves reduced lending volumes until the shortfall in regulatory capital has been remedie
